  "output": "I reviewed the actual codebase — this is a Python async job-scraper (`fetchers.py`, `store.py`, `filters.py`, `pipeline.py`, `notify.py`), not a React app, so I'm skipping the re-render section and focusing on the Python-equivalent concerns (redundant recomputation) plus the other four categories.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (`store.py:55-74`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, it runs a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With boards like Amazon/Microsoft/Google returning hundreds to thousands of listings per run, this is hundreds to thousands of individual round trips to SQLite every 12h cron run.\n\n```python\n# current — one SELECT + one INSERT/UPDATE per job, in a Python loop\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\n**Fix**: batch-load existing hashes with one (chunked) `IN` query, then use `executemany` for inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        qs = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        for row in self.conn.execute(\n                f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qs})\", chunk):\n            existing[row[\"key\"]] = row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    inserts, updates, touches = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touches.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id,\n            title, url, location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n            content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            inserts)\n    if updates:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n            WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touches:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touches)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(n) round trips into O(n/500 + 3).\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:11-27`)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** — every job re-compiles the identical set of keyword regexes from scratch. With a fetched batch of thousands of jobs, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls for the same handful of patterns.\n\n```python\n# filters.py — compile once, not per job\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                     locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nAnd change `match()`'s type hints/usage so `include`/`exclude` are treated as already-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` (drop the `_compile()` calls inside `match`).\n\n## 3. Caching opportunity — fetchers ignore what's already known (biggest win)\n\n`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, etc. paginate until a page returns **no ID unseen within this run** (`fresh = [... if j.external_id not in seen]`, `fetchers.py` throughout). Since each page has unique IDs, `fresh` is never empty until the board itself runs out — meaning **every single scheduled run (12h cron, per your commit history) re-walks the entire board from page 1**, even though these sources are sorted newest-first (`t_create`, `postedTs`, `posted_date`).\n\nThe `Store` already knows every previously-seen `external_id`/`content_hash`, but fetchers never see the `Store` — dedup only happens after the full fetch completes, in `pipeline.py:43`.\n\n**Fix sketch**: pass a `known: set[str]` (existing keys for that source/company) into the fetch loop for newest-first sources, and stop paginating once a page returns nothing new relative to the DB, not just relative to this run:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source, known: set[str] = frozenset()) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    for pg in range(max_pages):\n        data = await _get_json(...)\n        jobs_raw = (data or {}).get(\"jobs\") or []\n        batch = parse_amazon(company, jobs_raw)\n        fresh = [j for j in batch if j.external_id not in seen]\n        if not fresh:\n            break\n        seen.update(j.external_id for j in fresh)\n        jobs.extend(fresh)\n        # NEW: stop early once every ID on this page is already in the store —\n        # newest-first sort means everything after this is old news too.\n        if all(j.external_id in known for j in batch):\n            break\n    return jobs\n```\n\nFor boards with thousands of roles and `max_pages` in the 30–40 range, this could cut steady-state HTTP calls (and Google/Apple/Microsoft's rate-limit exposure) by an order of magnitude after the first run, since only the handful of genuinely new postings need to be paged through.\n\n## 4. Minor redundant computation — `content_hash` computed twice on the update path\n\n`Job.content_hash` (`models.py:66-69`) is a plain `@property` — it hashes on every access, not memoized. In `Store.diff()`'s \"changed\" branch, it's computed once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_update`'s `job.to_row()`. Cheap (SHA-256 over a short string) but free to fix — compute once and reuse:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs):\n    ...\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = job.content_hash  # compute once\n        row = cur.execute(...).fetchone()\n        if row is None:\n            ...\n        elif row[\"content_hash\"] != h:\n            changed.append(job)\n            self._update(cur, job, now, content_hash=h)  # pass through instead of recomputing\n```\n\n(Folds naturally into the batch rewrite in #1 anyway, since `job.to_row()` is only called once per job there.)\n\n## 5. Memory footprint (not a leak — process is short-lived per cron run)\n\nSince this is a per-invocation CLI process (not a long-running server), there's no classic leak, but peak memory during a run is worth noting: every parsed `Job` carries `raw=j` (the full source JSON, e.g. Apple/Workday payloads), and it's only dropped in `to_row()` right before persisting (`models.py:73`). With `concurrency=8` sources fetched concurrently and multi-thousand-role boards (Apple ~6,400 roles per the comment in `fetchers.py:456`), you're holding many full JSON blobs in memory simultaneously for data that's discarded before the DB write. If memory becomes a concern, dropping `raw` at parse time for large boards where it's unused (only Google/Apple/Netflix/Microsoft keep a minimal `raw={\"id\": ...}` already — the ones still storing the *whole* upstream dict, like `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `parse_phenom`, are the ones to trim) would reduce peak RSS.\n\n## Priority order\n1. **#3 (skip already-known pages)** — highest impact, cuts real network/latency cost on every scheduled run.\n2. **#1 (batch diff)** — straightforward, meaningfully reduces SQLite round trips.\n3. **#2 (precompile regex)** — trivial fix, real win on large batches.\n4. **#4/#5** — low priority, cheap or purely defensive.\n",
